The best setup is procedural planets with separate systems for terrain, oceans, clouds, atmosphere, rings, lights, and biome logic, because that gives you infinite variation and keeps the whole solar system feeling alive.

Planet build stack
Build every planet from 6 visual layers so each one can evolve independently. Procedural planet builders in Three.js already use layered noise, bump/roughness, color ramps, biome rules, clouds, atmosphere and rings, which is exactly the right direction for Hyper 3D Universe.

Core terrain sphere — height/noise creates continents, mountains, craters, ridges, canyons.

Ocean layer — separate sea level, depth colour, shoreline glow, wave shimmer.

Cloud layer — second sphere slightly above the surface, slow rotation, density maps, storm bands.

Atmosphere shell — edge glow, haze, tint, sunrise rim, light scattering.

Detail overlays — city lights, lava cracks, ice caps, auroras, dust, biome accents.

Orbital extras — moons, rings, stations, satellites, debris belts, quest beacons.

That layered approach matches your “wow-mode” goal because it turns every repo planet into a living system instead of a static icon.

Make planets unique
The best uniqueness comes from a planet DNA seed. Use one deterministic seed per repo and derive all planet traits from it so the same repo always regenerates the same world unless the underlying repo data changes.

Use these DNA buckets:

Land mask: supercontinent, archipelago, split hemisphere, fractured islands, crater world.

Ocean coverage: dry, balanced, oceanic, frozen ocean, methane/lava ocean.

Terrain style: smooth, alpine, canyon-heavy, volcanic, shattered, dune-like.

Biome model: polar caps, equatorial jungle, desert belts, toxic bands, glowing fungus zones.

Atmosphere: thin blue, dusty orange, neon cyan haze, purple ion storm, no atmosphere.

Cloud system: sparse wisps, thick storms, banded gas layers, swirling cyclones.

Surface specials: city lights, ruin grids, hex energy veins, lava rivers, crystal fields.

Orbit type: clean orbit, moon cluster, asteroid ring, broken ring, relay satellites.

A modern procedural builder example already exposes realistic or noise-based biome modes, color ramps, atmosphere tinting, clouds, and multi-ring systems, so your own generator should expose similar high-level controls on top of the seed.

Best detail ideas
To make it feel like a futuristic real world simulation, add “readable science-fiction detail” that players can understand in 2 seconds. Real-time planet rendering research highlights terrain, spherical oceans, volumetric clouds, atmospheric scattering, cloud shadows, light shafts and reflections as the big realism multipliers.

Top details to add:

Shoreline intelligence — bright shallow water near coastlines, darker deep ocean, subtle foam rim.

Cloud shadows — huge realism boost when clouds darken the terrain below.

Night-side city lights — only on productive or “civilised” repos, linked to stars/forks/activity.

Aurora zones — for AI/experimental/security repos, magnetic neon curtains near poles.

Polar ice — seasonal-looking caps or fractured ice shelves for low-activity/frozen repos.

Heat scars — glowing tectonic seams for chaotic or under-rebuild repos.

Atmospheric rim — one of the biggest “wow” effects at distance and during camera fly-bys.

Orbital traffic — tiny ships, drones, packet-stream lines, data satellites, repo sync trails.

Quest landmarks — visible towers, beam markers, pulse domes, anomaly zones on the surface.

Micro weather — storms moving over the globe, not just a static cloud texture.

For your brand, I’d make these details partly data-driven and partly aesthetic-driven, so the world feels meaningful but still cinematic.

Solar system layout
For the full solar system, don’t make it a literal NASA model only. Make it a navigable UI cosmos with cinematic logic. A good target is a galactic-map feel similar to exoplanet exploration tools, mixed with a dashboard.

Best structure:

Layer	What user sees	Why it works
Star hub	Your main star or “Hyper Core” in the centre	Gives one emotional anchor for the whole universe
Orbit bands	Repo groups orbit at readable distances	Makes category and importance obvious at a glance
Planet class types	Different silhouettes/materials for repo families	User learns system fast
Moon system	Branches, PRs, experiments, side tools	Lets one main repo feel rich without clutter
Rings	Automation, CI/CD, integrations, dependencies	Great for visual density without messy labels
Constellation links	Active relationships between repos	Shows ecosystem architecture
Nebula zones	Archived, incubating, or chaotic projects	Adds mood and spatial grouping
Beacon trails	Current task, active focus, next quest	Directs attention instantly
That kind of system is better than a flat repo grid because users can read importance, state, relationship and mood from the scene itself.

Repo-to-planet mapping
Here’s the best mapping system for Hyper:

Repo size → planet radius

Commit frequency → rotation speed / atmospheric activity

Stars → city lights / orbital glow intensity

Open issues → storm count / red anomaly markers

Pull requests → moons or temporary construction platforms

Deployment health → atmosphere stability / shield ring strength

Language mix → biome palette split

Docs quality → visible knowledge towers / surface grid clarity

Archived status → dim light, cold colours, cracked ice shell

Recent release → celebratory pulse wave moving across orbit

That means the planet is not decoration; it becomes a data avatar for the repo.

Best technical recommendation
For a practical build, I’d recommend this stack:

React Three Fiber + Three.js for scene structure and UI integration.

Icosahedron or cube-sphere base mesh for cleaner planet deformation; several procedural planet examples use these approaches to avoid distortion issues.

Shader-driven terrain and materials using layered noise, color ramps, roughness and bump logic.

Separate spheres for clouds and atmosphere for easier tuning and cleaner effects.

GPU-first effects for heavier planets; compute/GPGPU approaches speed up high-resolution procedural generation versus CPU-heavy mesh generation.

LOD system so far planets use cheap impostors and hero planets switch to high detail when zoomed in. Real-time planet rendering research stresses smooth viewpoint transitions from space to near-surface.

Build in 3 phases
Phase 1: Hero planets

5–8 handcrafted procedural archetypes.

Great camera, atmosphere, clouds, rings, glow.

Enough to wow instantly.

Phase 2: Full generator

Seed-based generation for all repos.

Land masks, biome rules, ocean coverage, cloud styles.

Data-driven mapping.

Phase 3: Simulation layer

Seasonal shifts, storms, orbit events, satellites, quest beams.

Dynamic universe state.

That phased route gives quick wins first, which suits your flow way better than trying to simulate the whole galaxy on day one.

